	<text>
		<body>
				<p>Re<hi rend="sup">d</hi> Sir</p>
			<p rend="indent(1)">Herewith I enclose 5&#36; you will please to give my ap <add>&#63;</add> with<lb/> three Dollars.  I re<hi rend="sup">d</hi> 75&#47;100 for 12 numbers address to F W. my care&#44; this person<lb/> could not afford to pay the amt. of subscription at once he paid me 25&#47;100 for each<lb/> 4 numbers&#44; as you have discontinued sending to him let it remain so.</p>
			<p rend="indent(1)">I am not aware that you still send to <placeName>Beloit</placeName>.  I mentioned<lb/> this to my son he has neglected to reply. he will be here soon and if he is<lb/> <sic>receving</sic> the Occident&#44; he will desire me to settle his a&#47;c.  I have been<lb/> frequently <sic>disapointed</sic> in not receiving the Weekly Nos. regularly on one<lb/> ocassion I was 2 weeks without getting any.  There are several persons here<lb/> who have met the same <sic>disapointment</sic>.  This should be <sic>enquired</sic> after&#8212;</p>
			<p rend="indent(1)">This Post will bring you a packet for publication.  I have reason<lb/> to believe the subject will meet yr. approval&#44; and induce you to afford<lb/> them a space to print them&#44; as they are arranged&#44; the interest I have in<lb/> the subject I seek to advocate&#44; induces me to say&#44; I shall be glad to see them on<lb/> record&#44; to continue them in any other manner would render the subject unintell<lb/>igible&#44; and in that case it would be better not to insert them at all<lb/>  I have two more chapt. on the same subject for continuation&#44; they<lb/> will occupy less space than these now sent.  I will send them on in due<lb/> time for publication.  Our Family have been residing all the summer in<lb/> the <sic>cuntry</sic>&#44; we have only removed into the city again a few days back.</p>
			<p rend="indent(1)">I shall have now leisure time to <hi rend="underline">copy</hi> what I have already written</p>
			<p rend="indent(2)">In a private conversation with <persName>Jo. Abraham</persName> who is now<lb/> <add>Hebrew</add> of the <add>&#63;</add>way <add>&#63;</add> he assures me that he has heard both the<lb/> Doctors declare that they are opposed to meet any convention they admit<lb/> the orthodox have the majority but not the wisdom</p>
			<p rend="indent(1)"><persName>Dr. Wise</persName> is <sic>urgeing</sic> his members to build a Temple the seats<lb/> to be made &#38; sold for a family&#44; the Gent. &#38; their wives&#44; with their hair uncovered<lb/> and many other improvements <add>&#63;</add> will follow the same plan<lb/> the Doctor only is waiting to see the result of <add>&#63;</add> when he will carry<lb/> his plans.  The Roof of the <add>&#63;</add>way <add>&#63;</add> requires a new roof with other costly<lb/> improvements which must come from the wealthy&#44; and they are the<lb/> majority.  It is time that some attempt should be made to check those<lb/> unholy proceedings.yours in haste</p>
			<p rend="indent(5)"><persName role="author">F Bruel</persName></p>
		</body>
